Why...yes. :)

Our Java implementation persists chromosomes in XML. 
Here&#39;s an example of a generational champion from a
successful XOR run:

&lt;chromosome id=&quot;2853&quot; primary-parent-id=&quot;2763&quot;&gt;
&lt;neuron id=&quot;0&quot; type=&quot;IN&quot;/&gt;
&lt;neuron id=&quot;1&quot; type=&quot;IN&quot;/&gt;
&lt;neuron id=&quot;2&quot; type=&quot;IN&quot;/&gt;
&lt;neuron id=&quot;3&quot; type=&quot;OUT&quot;/&gt;
&lt;connection id=&quot;4&quot; src-id=&quot;0&quot; dest-id=&quot;3&quot;
weight=&quot;-1.3731676929130425&quot;/&gt;
&lt;connection id=&quot;5&quot; src-id=&quot;1&quot; dest-id=&quot;3&quot;
weight=&quot;-1.208831769841949&quot;/&gt;
&lt;connection id=&quot;6&quot; src-id=&quot;2&quot; dest-id=&quot;3&quot;
weight=&quot;-0.853548931074944&quot;/&gt;
&lt;neuron id=&quot;16&quot; type=&quot;HID&quot;/&gt;
&lt;connection id=&quot;17&quot; src-id=&quot;0&quot; dest-id=&quot;16&quot;
weight=&quot;5.635234190131094&quot;/&gt;
&lt;connection id=&quot;18&quot; src-id=&quot;16&quot; dest-id=&quot;3&quot;
weight=&quot;2.7205467728011365&quot;/&gt;
&lt;connection id=&quot;34&quot; src-id=&quot;2&quot; dest-id=&quot;16&quot;
weight=&quot;-3.3648746983653126&quot;/&gt;
&lt;connection id=&quot;40&quot; src-id=&quot;1&quot; dest-id=&quot;16&quot;
weight=&quot;4.812986451760211&quot;/&gt;
&lt;/chromosome&gt;

It&#39;s pretty self-explanatory.  This chromosome is a
mutated clone (it has a single parent).  Chromosomes
that result from crossover have a primary and
secondary parent.

We also use XML to persist information about runs, and
we use XSL style sheets to convert the XML into SVG
for display purposes.

